1) Identify the code smell and provide fix.
Optional<User> user = userRepository.findById(id);
if (user.isPresent()) {
    return user.get().getEmail();
} else {
    return "unknown"; //
}

1. isPresent() + get() anti-pattern — defeats the entire purpose of Optional. It's just a verbose null-check.
2. user.get() without guard is risky — if someone refactors the if away, NoSuchElementException at runtime.
3. Verbose & imperative — Optional API provides declarative methods purpose-built for this exact pattern.


// ✅ FIX 1 — map() + orElse() — most idiomatic
return userRepository.findById(id)
        .map(User::getEmail)
        .orElse("unknown");


2) Identify the code smell and provide fix.

// ❌ BAD — NPE if getEmail() returns null
   Optional<String> email = Optional.of(user.getEmail());

// ✅ ofNullable — safe, returns Optional.empty() if null
Optional<String> email = Optional.ofNullable(user.getEmail());

// ✅ No intermediate Optional variable — clean pipeline
String email = Optional.ofNullable(user)
        .map(User::getEmail)                          // null-safe
        .filter(e -> !e.isBlank())                    // guard empty string
        .orElse("unknown");